The first time I knew about Wuhan was through Douyin, when I saw my teachers and colleagues in Wuhan, wearing masks for a long time, working for a long time, and some even collapsed physically. Later, I learned that one of my classmates, because to support the fever clinic infection, let me very sad.

So I submitted a challenge to our hospital in the first place. I was one of the first to set out on New Year's Eve. But on December twenty-nine, the day I went to the morning shift, our department came to a patient, he is from Wuhan back, both lungs are white, very serious, need tracheal intubation.

Endotracheal intubation is a great threat to medical staff. In 2003, when we intubated a patient in SARS, a room full of medical staff could have collapsed. And we don't have a lot of people who know how to intubate, so we had to do it ourselves.

At that time, there were not enough protective articles. It happened that our leaders left the protective clothing of SARS in 2003, so we forced ourselves to wear the clothes of that year. No N95 mask, just wear two surgical masks, no active air shield, just wear goggles, try to protect themselves, to do tracheal intubation.

After we intubated the patient, we were all put under medical quarantine. But happily, on the second day of the Lunar New Year, the patient tested negative for both nucleic acids, and was ruled out in the current alert mode. After I regained my freedom, I called our leader again and asked to go to Wuhan again.

And gloves are often small, after putting on will often feel the hand is very painful. Two masks make breathing a luxury. It's like someone's covering your mouth. Can't breathe.

To get the medicine, I told my doctor back home that I was HIV positive
38:24 Blackie

I usually work in Wuhan, during the Spring Festival, I returned to my hometown, Jingzhou, has been staying.

I started treatment in about 2014, and it's been almost five years now. The last withdrawal was in December, about a year ago. Traditionally, we would go to the hospital a week or 15 days before we ran out of the medicine and pick it up once every three months, depending on how much we had.

Normally, if we're going out of town, we double up on the meds just in case. So if we're going by the usual standards, this time I've got a pretty good dose, because it's going to be a month. But I didn't expect to spend so much time at home because of the epidemic.

From the end of December, the whole city of Wuhan began to spread some news of the epidemic. But before Zhong Nanshan spoke, life in Wuhan was normal. After Zhong Nanshan spoke, the mood across Wuhan was very strange. The next day when you go out, you'll find that everyone is wearing a mask and is consciously keeping their distance.

We had the day off on January 22nd, the day I took the bus home. From the time I was in my hometown, you will find that Wuhan has already entered a very alert state. Whether you take the subway, the train, or the bus, your temperature will be checked and you will be wearing a mask when you leave or enter the station. You are not allowed to leave or enter the station without wearing a mask.

After arriving home in the evening, I received a message from my colleague in Wuhan: Wuhan decided to close the city at 12 o'clock that night.

Our village is the village on the second day of the New Year. Village cadres and party members began to guard all the junctions and main roads in the villages. From now on, the prevention and control measures will be more and more strict. Until now, the organization department in the village was not allowed to go out unless there were serious special circumstances such as illness.

By the time I got home 20 days or so, I realized that I might not be able to keep my medication until the outbreak was completely over. So I set about making some preparations to make sure that the drugs would keep up.

HIV infection is generally in the place of residence or residence where the drug, I was in Wuhan drug, so I first went to get in touch with Wuhan Disease Control. From there, I learned that I could get a month's supply of medicine at our local treatment center through a referral from the Wuhan CDC. Then I went to our local county CDC to confirm that they could supply me with drugs.

On January 26th China's antiviral drug issued a circular on guaranteeing free travel for people living with HIV in other places.

At this point, there's another, more important thing to do, and that's how to get the medicine. Judging by our local blockade, I wouldn't have been able to get out of the house without a special reason.

So I had to go to the township health center, our local epidemic prevention headquarters, and ask them for proof. But, because my grandfather was a doctor, 90% of the doctors in my village knew me. If I wanted a certificate from a village doctor, that meant I had to tell them about my condition.

At first I just told the doctor I had a chronic disease and needed to go into the city to get medicine. But the doctor for strictly control the number of travel considerations, and further pressed the reason, I had to tell the truth.

I hadn't come out to my family and told them I was sick, so I had to lie to them and tell them that I had a chronic sinus attack, that it was serious, and that I needed to get medicine before I left the house.

On the way to get my medicine, I went through nearly five checkpoints. Each time I have taken the initiative to show proof of travel, very smoothly through. In the process, I also found that there are a lot of people who did not prove to try to muddle through, but were blocked back.

The whole thing was handled quite smoothly, I did not have too big mood swings, only to find the hospital to help me open evidence, some internal fluctuations. I don't really mind people knowing about my condition, but it's hard for me to accept that my parents are being judged for it.

For now, it's just a matter of what happens next. To determine when to return to Wuhan, if the time will be extended, I may do the second step, try to get a second batch of drugs, to ensure that the amount of drugs to support the end of the road closure.

For the infected, I think the most important thing is identity, you have to accept where you are now, in the follow-up work and treatment will not feel very anxious. Many people may be in a state of ignorance, which is actually more terrible than getting sick.

When you have a deep understanding of what to do when you get sick, and how to treat it, you don't feel that your life is going to be very dark. And you feel like we're okay, like we can live like normal people, and it's not as bad as you think.

38:24 Blackie

I usually work in Wuhan, during the Spring Festival, I returned to my hometown, Jingzhou, has been staying.

I started treatment in about 2014, and it's been almost five years now. The last withdrawal was in December, about a year ago. Traditionally, we would go to the hospital a week or 15 days before we ran out of the medicine and pick it up once every three months, depending on how much we had.

Normally, if we're going out of town, we double up on the meds just in case. So if we're going by the usual standards, this time I've got a pretty good dose, because it's going to be a month. But I didn't expect to spend so much time at home because of the epidemic.

From the end of December, the whole city of Wuhan began to spread some news of the epidemic. But before Zhong Nanshan spoke, life in Wuhan was normal. After Zhong Nanshan spoke, the mood across Wuhan was very strange. The next day when you go out, you'll find that everyone is wearing a mask and is consciously keeping their distance.

We had the day off on January 22nd, the day I took the bus home. From the time I was in my hometown, you will find that Wuhan has already entered a very alert state. Whether you take the subway, the train, or the bus, your temperature will be checked and you will be wearing a mask when you leave or enter the station. You are not allowed to leave or enter the station without wearing a mask.

After arriving home in the evening, I received a message from my colleague in Wuhan: Wuhan decided to close the city at 12 o'clock that night.

Our village is the village on the second day of the New Year. Village cadres and party members began to guard all the junctions and main roads in the villages. From now on, the prevention and control measures will be more and more strict. Until now, the organization department in the village was not allowed to go out unless there were serious special circumstances such as illness.

By the time I got home 20 days or so, I realized that I might not be able to keep my medication until the outbreak was completely over. So I set about making some preparations to make sure that the drugs would keep up.

HIV infection is generally in the place of residence or residence where the drug, I was in Wuhan drug, so I first went to get in touch with Wuhan Disease Control. From there, I learned that I could get a month's supply of medicine at our local treatment center through a referral from the Wuhan CDC. Then I went to our local county CDC to confirm that they could supply me with drugs.

On January 26th China's antiviral drug issued a circular on guaranteeing free travel for people living with HIV in other places.

At this point, there's another, more important thing to do, and that's how to get the medicine. Judging by our local blockade, I wouldn't have been able to get out of the house without a special reason.

So I had to go to the township health center, our local epidemic prevention headquarters, and ask them for proof. But, because my grandfather was a doctor, 90% of the doctors in my village knew me. If I wanted a certificate from a village doctor, that meant I had to tell them about my condition.

At first I just told the doctor I had a chronic disease and needed to go into the city to get medicine. But the doctor for strictly control the number of travel considerations, and further pressed the reason, I had to tell the truth.

I hadn't come out to my family and told them I was sick, so I had to lie to them and tell them that I had a chronic sinus attack, that it was serious, and that I needed to get medicine before I left the house.

On the way to get my medicine, I went through nearly five checkpoints. Each time I have taken the initiative to show proof of travel, very smoothly through. In the process, I also found that there are a lot of people who did not prove to try to muddle through, but were blocked back.

The whole thing was handled quite smoothly, I did not have too big mood swings, only to find the hospital to help me open evidence, some internal fluctuations. I don't really mind people knowing about my condition, but it's hard for me to accept that my parents are being judged for it.

For now, it's just a matter of what happens next. To determine when to return to Wuhan, if the time will be extended, I may do the second step, try to get a second batch of drugs, to ensure that the amount of drugs to support the end of the road closure.

For the infected, I think the most important thing is identity, you have to accept where you are now, in the follow-up work and treatment will not feel very anxious. Many people may be in a state of ignorance, which is actually more terrible than getting sick.

When you have a deep understanding of what to do when you get sick, and how to treat it, you don't feel that your life is going to be very dark. And you feel like we're okay, like we can live like normal people, and it's not as bad as you think.
